Eastern Amazonia—focuses on their concepts of personhood, death, and divinity. Building upon ethnographic description and interpretation, Viveiros de Castro addresses the central aspect of the Arawete's concept of divinity—consumption—showing how its cannibalistic expression differs radically from traditional representations of other Amazonian societies. He situates the Araweté in contemporary anthropology as a people whose vision of the world is complex, tragic, and dynamic, and whose society commands our attention for its extraordinary openness to exteriority and transformation. For the Araweté the person is always in transition, an outlook expressed in the mythology of their gods, whose cannibalistic ways they imitate. From the Enemy's Point of View argues that current concepts of society as a discrete, bounded entity which maintains a difference between "interior" and "exterior" are wholly inappropriate in this and in many other Amazonian societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aarawete, amazon, imperialism, religion, identity, self, personhood, death, divinity, humanity, cosmology, ritual, ceremony, rite, tradition, indigenous, tupi-guarani, amazonia, consumption, cannibalism, anthropology, transformation, exteriority, transition, gods, mythology, folk narrative, folklore, brazil, nonfiction, sociology, landscape, nature, beer, honey, shaman, tribe, vengeance, sacrifice, flesh.1 aHoward, Catherine V.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226768830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226768830/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aGBV-deGruyter-alles